# Frontend engineering conventions

Match the existing codebase. The live patterns are in `ContractDetail.tsx`,
`SubmitHours.tsx`, `NewContract.tsx`, `main.tsx`, and `src/api/*`.

## Data layer
- All HTTP goes through a typed function in `src/api/`. Components never call
  `fetch` or the `api` object directly. Add a function (e.g. in
  `api/timesheets.ts`) and import it.
- Reuse the `api.get/post/patch/delete` helpers and the `ApiError` class.
- Reuse shared types from `src/api/client.ts` (`Contract`, `TimesheetEntry`, ...).
  Do not redefine them.

## React Query
- Server state lives in React Query. Do not cache server data in `useState`.
- queryKey shape is `[entity, paramsObject]`, e.g.
  `['timesheets', { status: 'submitted' }]`, matching existing keys.
- Dependent queries use `enabled`.
- Mutations use `useMutation` + `queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey })` on
  success, as in `NewContract` and `SubmitHours`. Do not hand-roll refetching.
- Honour the global defaults in `main.tsx` (retry 1, staleTime 30s). Only override
  per-query with a reason.

## State
- Ephemeral UI state in `useState`. The only context is `useAuth`. Do not add a
  state library (Redux, Zustand, etc.).
- Derive values during render. Do not mirror derived data into state or sync it
  with `useEffect`. See `totalHours` in `ContractDetail`.
- Surface errors as a local message string rendered in the existing banner, the
  way the forms do. Map server field errors via `err instanceof ApiError` and
  `err.data.<field>` (see `NewContract` reading `end_date`).

## Numbers and money
- `hours` and `daily_rate` arrive as strings. Always `Number()` before
  arithmetic. Never concatenate them.
- Cost is hours times daily rate divided by 8 (the codebase day convention),
  formatted `£${value.toFixed(2)}` and labelled "est.". Put this in one helper and
  use it everywhere. Do not re-derive it inline.

## Routing and role gating
- Register new routes in `App.tsx`, wrapped in `<RequireAuth><Layout>…`.
- Gate by role the existing way: redirect unauthorised roles with
  `<Navigate to="…" replace />` based on `useAuth` flags (`isAdmin`,
  `isFreelancer`).
- Gate admin-only nav entries on `isAdmin` in `Nav.tsx`.
- Role behaviour (hidden vs disabled vs redirect) is defined in the UX spec. This
  rule only covers wiring it.

## Scope discipline
- Stay within the approval-inbox feature. Do not refactor or "fix" unrelated
  files, the backend, or the billing/developer stubs.
- If you spot a bug or rough edge outside scope, note it in the PR or a comment.
  Do not change it.
